  "Does not change it": "",
  "Decreases it": "",
  "Increases it": "",
  "A catalyst lowers the activation energy by providing an alternative reaction pathway, allowing more molecules to have sufficient energy to react.": "",
  "Is a catalyst consumed during the reaction?": "",
  "Yes, it is used up completely": "",
  "It depends on the type of catalyst": "",
  "It is partially consumed": "",
  "No, it is regenerated and can be reused": "",
  "A catalyst participates in the reaction mechanism but is regenerated by the end of the reaction cycle, so it is not consumed and can catalyze many reaction cycles.": "",
  "The Arrhenius equation relates the rate constant k to which variables?": "",
  "Concentration and volume": "",
  "Pressure and temperature": "",
  "Molar mass and density": "",
  "Temperature and activation energy": "",
  "The Arrhenius equation k = Ae^(-Ea/RT) relates the rate constant to the activation energy (Ea), temperature (T), and the frequency factor (A).": "",
  "What is the difference between a homogeneous and heterogeneous catalyst?": "",
  "A homogeneous catalyst is in the same phase as the reactants; a heterogeneous one is in a different phase": "",
  "Heterogeneous catalysts are always metals within the broader context of catalyst analysis": "",
  "Homogeneous catalysts work faster according to widely held views on this topic": "",
  "There is no difference when considering all relevant catalyst factors": "",
  "A homogeneous catalyst exists in the same phase (e.g., dissolved in the same solution) as the reactants, while a heterogeneous catalyst is in a different phase (e.g., a solid catalyst in a gas-phase reaction).": "",
  "Does a catalyst change the equilibrium position of a reversible reaction?": "",
  "No, it speeds up both forward and reverse reactions equally": "",
  "Yes, it shifts equilibrium toward products": "",
  "Yes, it shifts equilibrium toward reactants": "",
  "A catalyst lowers the activation energy for both the forward and reverse reactions equally, so equilibrium is reached faster but the position of equilibrium does not change.": "",
