  "What does 'energy profile' (or reaction coordinate diagram) mean?": "",
  "A chart showing temperature changes during a reaction": "",
  "A diagram showing how potential energy changes as reactants convert to products through the transition state": "",
  "A diagram of molecular orbitals": "",
  "A graph of concentration vs time": "",
  "An energy profile plots potential energy along the reaction coordinate, showing the energy levels of reactants, the transition state (activation energy peak), and products.": "",
  "What does 'active site' mean in the context of catalysis?": "",
  "The most reactive element in the reaction": "",
  "The specific location on a catalyst where reactant molecules bind and undergo reaction": "",
  "The highest energy point on the energy profile": "",
  "The area where products collect": "",
  "The active site is the specific region on a catalyst (or enzyme) surface where reactant molecules adsorb, interact, and undergo the chemical transformation.": "",
  "What does 'inhibitor' mean?": "",
  "A substance that changes the products": "",
  "A substance that speeds up a reaction": "",
  "A substance that slows down or prevents a chemical reaction": "",
  "A substance that shifts equilibrium": "",
  "An inhibitor is a substance that decreases the rate of a chemical reaction, often by blocking the active sites of a catalyst or by interfering with the reaction mechanism.": "",
  "What does 'adsorption' mean in heterogeneous catalysis?": "",
  "Molecules dissolving in the reaction solvent": "",
  "Molecules being repelled by the catalyst": "",
  "Molecules binding to the surface of the catalyst": "",
  "Molecules being absorbed into the bulk of the catalyst": "",
  "Adsorption is the process where reactant molecules bind to the surface of a heterogeneous catalyst, which weakens their bonds and facilitates the reaction.": "",
  "A car's catalytic converter contains platinum and palladium to convert toxic exhaust gases (CO, NOx) into harmless products (CO2, N2). At what point during a cold start is the converter least effective, and why?": "",
  "When the fuel is premium grade": "",
  "When the converter is cold, because the catalyst needs sufficient temperature to be effective": "",
  "During idling, because there is not enough O2": "",
  "At high engine speeds, because there is too much exhaust": "",
  "Catalytic converters require a minimum operating temperature (light-off temperature) to function. During cold starts, the catalyst has not yet reached this temperature and cannot effectively adsorb and convert the gases.": "",
  "A pharmaceutical company discovers that a reaction has Ea = 80 kJ/mol without a catalyst and Ea = 40 kJ/mol with a catalyst. By approximately what factor does the rate increase at 300 K? (R = 8.314 J/mol/K)": "",
  "About 10^7 times faster": "",
  "About 100 times faster": "",
  "About 1000 times faster": "",
  "About 2 times faster": "",
  "The ratio k_cat/k_uncat = e^((Ea_uncat - Ea_cat)/RT) = e^(40000/(8.314 x 300)) = e^(16.04) which is approximately 9 x 10^6, or roughly 10^7 times faster.": "",
  "Hydrogen peroxide (H2O2) decomposes slowly at room temperature. Adding a small amount of MnO2 causes rapid bubbling. If the MnO2 is filtered out and weighed afterward, it has the same mass. What does this demonstrate?": "",
  "MnO2 provides extra oxygen for the reaction": "",
  "MnO2 absorbs the hydrogen peroxide": "",
  "MnO2 acts as a catalyst, speeding up the reaction without being consumed": "",
  "MnO2 is a reactant that regenerates itself": "",
  "The unchanged mass of MnO2 proves it was not consumed. It acted as a heterogeneous catalyst, lowering the activation energy for H2O2 decomposition into water and oxygen gas.": "",
  "A student measures the rate constant for a reaction at two temperatures: k = 0.015 s^-1 at 300 K and k = 0.045 s^-1 at 320 K. Using the two-point Arrhenius equation, what is the approximate activation energy?": "",
  "About 27 kJ/mol": "",
  "About 8.3 kJ/mol": "",
  "About 44 kJ/mol": "",
  "About 100 kJ/mol": "",
  "ln(k2/k1) = (Ea/R)(1/T1 - 1/T2). ln(0.045/0.015) = (Ea/8.314)(1/300 - 1/320). ln(3) = Ea/8.314 x (2.083 x 10^-4). 1.099 = Ea x 2.506 x 10^-5. Ea = 43,800 J/mol or about 44 kJ/mol.": "",
  "Industrial ammonia synthesis uses an iron catalyst at 400-500 degrees C. Without the catalyst, the reaction would require even higher temperatures. A student asks: why not just use a higher temperature instead of a catalyst?": "",
  "Higher temperatures shift the equilibrium toward reactants (since the forward reaction is exothermic), reducing yield": "",
  "The catalyst is cheaper than heating": "",
  "Higher temperatures would decompose the iron": "",
  "Temperature has no effect on equilibrium": "",
  "The Haber process is exothermic, so increasing temperature shifts equilibrium toward reactants by Le Chatelier's principle. A catalyst allows a reasonable rate at a moderate temperature without sacrificing too much equilibrium yield.": "",
  "A biologist studies an enzyme-catalyzed reaction. At low substrate concentration, increasing substrate speeds up the reaction. At high substrate concentration, the rate plateaus. Why does the rate stop increasing?": "",
  "The temperature decreases": "",
  "The activation energy increases": "",
  "The enzyme is destroyed at high concentrations": "",
  "All enzyme active sites are occupied (saturated), so adding more substrate cannot increase the rate": "",
  "At saturation, every enzyme molecule has substrate bound to its active site. Additional substrate must wait for an active site to become free, creating a rate ceiling known as Vmax.": "",
  "A food manufacturer uses enzymes to convert starch to glucose. The process works well at 37 degrees C but fails at 80 degrees C, even though higher temperatures normally speed up reactions. What explains this?": "",
  "The glucose breaks down at 80 degrees C": "",
  "The enzyme denatures (loses its 3D structure) at 80 degrees C, destroying its catalytic activity": "",
  "The activation energy increases at 80 degrees C": "",
  "The starch becomes insoluble at 80 degrees C": "",
  "Enzymes are proteins whose catalytic activity depends on their precise 3D shape. At 80 degrees C, the protein unfolds (denatures), destroying the active site and eliminating catalytic function.": "",
  "The ozone layer is depleted by chlorine radicals from CFCs. One Cl atom can destroy ~100,000 O3 molecules because Cl is regenerated: Cl + O3 -> ClO + O2, then ClO + O -> Cl + O2. What role does Cl play?": "",
  "Cl is an inhibitor": "",
  "Cl is a product of ozone decomposition": "",
  "Cl is a reactant that is consumed": "",
  "Cl acts as a catalyst because it is regenerated after each cycle": "",
  "Chlorine is regenerated at the end of the two-step mechanism, making it a catalyst for ozone destruction. It speeds up the overall reaction O3 + O -> 2O2 without being consumed.": "",
  "A researcher compares the energy profile diagrams for a reaction with and without a catalyst. Both diagrams show the same reactant and product energy levels. What is different?": "",
  "The catalyzed pathway has a lower peak (lower activation energy) but the same overall energy change": "",
  "The products have lower energy in the catalyzed pathway": "",
  "The catalyzed pathway has a higher peak": "",
  "The reactants have higher energy in the catalyzed pathway": "",
  "A catalyst provides an alternative pathway with a lower activation energy (lower peak) but does not change the overall enthalpy change, so reactant and product energies remain the same.": "",
